# 🌿 The Journey at a Glance

Sarga 186 begins with a declaration of spiritual completion.

Kundadanta no longer merely understands that Brahman is the substratum of the world.

He sees the world itself as Brahman.

From there, Sage Vasiṣṭha carries the inquiry through a series of dissolutions.

First, the separation between Brahman and appearance is dissolved.

Then the separation between the seer and the seen.

Then the distinction between sentient and insentient.

Then the belief in creation and dissolution.

Then even the conceptual opposition between duality and unity.

What remains is not a blank void.

It is luminous Consciousness—

beginningless,

indivisible,

unaffected,

and appearing as every possible experience without ever becoming limited by any appearance.

The world is not rejected.

Its imagined independence is rejected.

The body is not denied.

Its claim to be the Self is denied.

Activity is not stopped.

The separate doer is seen through.

Multiplicity is not destroyed.

Its separation from Consciousness is understood to have never been real.

Thus this sarga does not ask us to abandon the universe.

It asks us to see it correctly.

A wave need not disappear to know that it is water.

A dream-image need not fight the dream to discover that it is mind.

The world need not vanish for Brahman to be realized.

Only the misunderstanding must vanish.

Then every form becomes transparent to the Formless.

Every movement shines in the Motionless.

Every object is known as an appearance in Consciousness.

And every experience quietly declares:

**Sarvaṁ khalvidaṁ Brahma—
All this, indeed, is Brahman.**

